  "output": "No React frontend here — this is a Python `asyncio` job-scraper (ATS fetchers → SQLite dedup → notifiers), so I focused on the SQL layer, hot loops, and network I/O instead. Here's what I found, ranked by impact.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (highest impact)\n\n`Store.diff()` runs one `SELECT` per job in a Python loop, then commits inserts/updates one at a time too. Amazon/Microsoft boards alone can hand back thousands of jobs per run (`max_pages=40` × 10/page), so this is thousands of round-trip queries per pipeline run instead of one.\n\n```python\n# store.py — batch lookup + batch write instead of per-job round trips\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 500):          # SQLite bind-param limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 500]\n        ph = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        rows = cur.execute(\n            f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({ph})\", chunk).fetchall()\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in rows})\n\n    new, changed = [], []\n    to_insert, to_update, to_touch = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev = existing.get(job.key)\n        h = job.content_hash                     # compute once (see #2)\n        row = {**job.to_row(content_hash=h), \"now\": now}\n        if prev is None:\n            new.append(job); to_insert.append(row)\n        elif prev != h:\n            changed.append(job); to_update.append(row)\n        else:\n            to_touch.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if to_insert: cur.executemany(INSERT_SQL, to_insert)\n    if to_update: cur.executemany(UPDATE_SQL, to_update)\n    if to_touch:  cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", to_touch)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nTurns `2N+` individual statements into `O(N/500)` selects + 3 batched `executemany` calls.\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job (`filters.py:11-27,44-55`)\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` **every time** — recompiling the same regex list from scratch for every single job in the run instead of once for the whole batch.\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])   # compiled once\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])   # compiled once\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include_re, exclude_re, locations, cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, include_re, exclude_re, locations, cutoff) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude_re and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude_re):\n        return False\n    if include_re and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include_re):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\nWith N jobs and K keywords this is O(N·K) unnecessary regex compiles → O(K) once + O(N·K) matches.\n\n## 3. Redundant computation — `content_hash` computed twice per row (`models.py:66-69`, `store.py:76-97`)\n\n`Job.content_hash` is a `@property` that runs a SHA-256 hash on every access. `diff()` reads it once for the comparison, then `_insert`/`_update` call `job.to_row()`, which reads it again — hashing every new/changed job twice. Cheap per-call, but pure waste at scale. Fixed above by threading the already-computed hash into `to_row(content_hash=h)`:\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self, content_hash: str | None = None) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)\n    d[\"key\"] = self.key\n    d[\"content_hash\"] = content_hash if content_hash is not None else self.content_hash\n    return d\n```\n\n## 4. Bonus (not asked, but the biggest wall-clock win): serial pagination in `fetchers.py`\n\nEvery paginated fetcher (`fetch_amazon`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_google`, `fetch_workday`, `fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_optiver`) awaits pages one at a time in a `for` loop — e.g. `fetch_amazon` (`fetchers.py:718-738`) does up to 40 sequential round trips. Several of these APIs return a total count on page 0 (Amazon's `hits`, Workday's `total`), so pages 2..N can be fetched concurrently instead:\n\n```python\nasync def fetch_amazon(client, source):\n    company = source.get(\"company\", \"amazon\")\n    url = \"https://www.amazon.jobs/en/search.json\"\n    base = {\"base_query\": source.get(\"query\", \"\"), \"sort\": \"recent\", \"result_limit\": 10}\n    max_pages = int(source.get(\"max_pages\", 40))\n\n    first = await _get_json(client, url, params={**base, \"offset\": 0},\n                            headers={\"Accept\": \"application/json\"})\n    jobs = parse_amazon(company, (first or {}).get(\"jobs\") or [])\n    seen = {j.external_id for j in jobs}\n    total = min((first or {}).get(\"hits\") or 0, max_pages * 10)\n\n    async def page(offset):\n        data = await _get_json(client, url, params={**base, \"offset\": offset},\n                               headers={\"Accept\": \"application/json\"})\n        return (data or {}).get(\"jobs\") or []\n\n    for raw in await asyncio.gather(*(page(o) for o in range(10, total, 10))):\n        fresh = [j for j in parse_amazon(company, raw) if j.external_id not in seen]\n        seen.update(j.external_id for j in fresh)\n        jobs.extend(fresh)\n    return jobs\n```\n\nThis also matters because `fetch_all`'s semaphore caps *source-level* concurrency at 8 (`fetchers.py:773`) — a source stuck doing 40 serial page fetches holds one of those 8 slots for the whole time, starving other sources' concurrency budget too.\n\n## Memory leaks / caching — nothing notable\n\n- `httpx.AsyncClient` lifecycle is correct (`fetch_all` closes it in a `finally`), `Store`/`sqlite3.Connection` are used via context managers everywhere — no leaked handles.\n- No React/frontend code exists in this repo, so there's nothing to check for re-renders.\n- Caching HTTP responses across runs isn't appropriate here — the whole point of the pipeline is fresh listings — so I didn't flag that as an opportunity.\n\n**Suggested priority:** fix #1 first (real N+1, biggest query-count reduction), then #2 (trivial, no risk), then #4 if wall-clock run time matters to you. #3 is a nice-to-have alongside #1 since you're already touching that code path.\n",
